        <article><![CDATA[<p>If you <strong>don&#39;t have Tanium Threat Response</strong>, or don&#39;t want to <strong>quarantine</strong> endpoints, you may skip this step. </p>
<p>If you do have the Tanium <strong>Threat Response</strong> module licensed and installed, and use it to &#39;quarantine&#39; endpoints, you may have configured custom Tanium packages to quarantine (or even un-quarantine) endpoints. <br />As per the <a title="Threat Response documentation" href="https://docs.tanium.com/threat_response/threat_response/isolating_endpoints.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow">Threat Response documentation</a>, this is recommended in order to preserve any customizations to the <em>taniumquarantine.dat</em> file that stores the quarantine configuration settings, associated with the quarantine packages.</p>
<p>There are three separate packages for quarantining endpoints; one for Windows, one for Linux, and one for Mac. These settings will allow you to enter the exact name of the packages you currently use to quarantine endpoints, if you use custom quarantine packages. If you don&#39;t, you may skip this step. </p>
<p>Note: After syncing packages from Tanium into the <a title="Tanium Packages" href="x_taniu_tan_core_tanium_package_list.do" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow">Tanium Packages</a> table using <a title="this Scheduled Script" href="sysauto_script.do?sys_id&#61;00d7b0dc2f2f70501ba85d492799b6b1" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow">this Scheduled Script</a>, your custom packages (along with all others) should be shown in that table. The package names that you set these properties to, should each <em>exactly match</em> the name of some package that can be found in that table. </p>]]></article>
